## Common Mistakes

- Hardcoding API keys directly in scripts instead of using environment variables or secure vault configs, exposing credentials when sharing templates
- Ignoring API rate limits and quotas, causing service blocks or unexpected costs—AI APIs have strict per-minute and per-day limits
- Processing entire vault content without chunking, leading to token limit errors and excessive API costs—always chunk content over ~2000 words
- Not handling API errors gracefully in scripts, causing templates to fail silently or hang indefinitely without user feedback
- Over-automating metadata creation with excessive auto-linking, generating noisy backlinks that don't represent actual conceptual relationships
- Sending sensitive or private vault content to external AI APIs without understanding data handling policies—assume anything sent may be stored
- Creating circular dependencies where one automated template triggers another, leading to infinite loops or duplicate content
- Neglecting to sanitize user input in QuickAdd macros, allowing malicious content or broken YAML frontmatter from poorly formatted capture fields
- Not versioning template scripts, losing working configurations after experimenting with changes or system updates
- Relying entirely on AI summarization without manual review, allowing AI hallucinations or context drifts to pollute your knowledge base


## Best Practices

- Use environment variables or a dedicated API keys note that's excluded from sync/externally encrypted rather than hardcoding credentials in scripts
- Implement exponential backoff retry logic for API calls, with user-friendly error messages that explain what failed and what to do next
- Design templates to work incrementally—process only the current note or recent changes rather than scanning the entire vault on every execution
- Start with simple, reliable automations before adding AI complexity; get the baseline working first, then enhance with intelligence layers
- Document every automation in your vault with a dedicated workflow documentation note, including what triggers it and expected outputs
- Test automations with edge cases: empty content, extremely long notes, special characters, non-English text, and unusual file paths
- Use separate API keys for different purposes (summarization, embedding, RAG) to track costs and isolate issues when problems arise
- Create a manual review step for AI-generated content before auto-inserting; use 'Draft' status that requires explicit approval to promote to final
- Maintain a changelog for template versions, noting what changed and why, so you can revert if a new version introduces problems
- Schedule periodic audits of auto-generated metadata—review auto-links for accuracy, clean up stale tags, and verify backlinks reflect actual connections
- Use semantic chunking strategies that respect logical boundaries (paragraphs, headers, list items) rather than arbitrary character cuts
- Implement vault-wide search to verify duplicate automations or conflicting template behaviors before rolling out new scripts

